content.problemStatement:
In C++, you can use a `for` loop to access each character of a string one by one. This is useful when you want to **print**, **analyze**, or **modify** characters in a string.

The loop uses an index that starts from `0` and goes up to `string.length() - 1`, allowing you to access each character using `string[i]`.

---
**Example**

```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {
    string name = "Hello"; // Predefined string

    // Loop through each character in the string using index
    for (int i = 0; i < name.length(); i++) {
        cout << name[i] << endl; // Print the character at index i
    }

    return 0; 
}
```
**Expected Output:**
```default
H
e
l
l
o
```

